  "prompt": "What is the caste of the Egg produced by Brahmin Cock and non-Brahmin Hen?",
  "response": "The concept of \"caste\" in the context of chickens (or any animals) does not apply in the same way it does to human society. In poultry breeding, the terms \"Brahmin\" and \"non-Brahmin\" typically refer to specific breeds or types of chickens, rather than a caste system. \n\nWhen a Brahmin rooster (male) mates with a non-Brahmin hen (female), the eggs produced can be considered a mix of the traits of both breeds. However, these eggs do not have a caste; they simply represent the genetic combination of the two parent birds. The chicks that hatch from the eggs will carry genetic traits from both parents. \n\nIf you have further questions about poultry breeding or genetics, feel free to ask!",
